entry.title: [PIX] Let the browser know if an invalid PIX code was detected
entry.content:
Before this patch, the FacilitatedPaymentsAgent in the renderer process

sent only a boolean that was true when a valid PIX was found. Not

running PIX code detection, absence of PIX code, or an invalid PIX code

resulted in the boolean "false".



The boolean made it hard to distinguish whether Chrome is failing to

find a PIX code or is failing to validate it, which is possible when a

page contains the indicator string "0014br.gov.bcb.pix", but the rest of

the string does not follow a valid PIX code format.



This patch changes the mojom IPC to return an enum with four possible

values instead of the existing boolean.



After this patch, the FacilitatedPaymentsAgent in the renderer process

sends an enum with one of the following four values:

1) PIX code detection was not run.

2) No PIX code was found.

3) An invalid PIX code was found.

4) A valid PIX code was found.



Bug: 324765365

entry.title: Record number of suspended notifications on PRE_UNSUBSCRIBE.
entry.content:
Let the NotificationPlatformBridge record a histogram that counts

the suspended notifications on each PRE_UNSUBSCRIBE action. The

total count in this histogram can also be compared to

entry.title: [Viewport Segments API] Implement Android support.
entry.content:
This patch implements the Android support for the Viewport Segments API

using the Window Layout API from Android (like the Device Posture).



This patch also remove some leftover code landed couple of years ago to

initially support the Viewport Segments API through ViewAndroid (because

the Device Posture API wasn't yet in the picture). The whole implementation

never made it upstream anyway.



This patch also refactor the semantics from DevicePosturePlatformProvider.

Instead of sending the segments from the platform we send the display feature

bounds. We send only one display feature info because that's the only supported

use case right now in chromium/blink. When devices with multiple hinges/folds

come around we would need to change a bunch of other places in blink/content

to support that so let's not complicate the current implementation with an

array of display features coming from the platform.

entry.title: Protected Audience: Detect inconsistent PageImpl during auction.
entry.content:
This is a fix for a long standing issue in Protected Audience (PA).



Through a PA auction, the PageImpl of the auction initiator frame is

assumed to stay the same.



However, this is not true in certain scenario. See

MainFrameDocumentAssociatedDataChangesOnSameSiteNavigation in

SitePerProcessBrowserTest.



This CL fixes this by detecting the inconsistency of PageImpl and

aborting the auction.



This is done by keeping a weak pointer to the PageImpl in the RHFI of

the auction initiator frame, when AdAuctionServiceImpl is constructed

as part of the first PA API call.



The weak pointer is checked:

1. Before the start of the auction.

2. When OnAuctionComplete callback is invoked.



If the check fails, the auction is aborted.



This weak pointer is reset when there is a cross-document navigation,

and the frame does not go into bfcache.



This change is gated by a default-enabled feature flag to allow us to

turn it off via finch.



For reviewers not familiar with this issue, the linked crbug below

contains the relevant info. There has been numerous discussions and

start reading from comment#61 should be sufficient.

https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1422301#c61



Bug: 1422301, 936696

entry.title: [SAA] Remove unused histogram
entry.content:
Despite best intentions, this histogram isn't especially useful since

98% of records are "no opt-in, no grant", as expected. The only

possibly-interesting case is "opt-in, no grant", but this is easily

explained by auto-resolved rSA calls due to cookie settings or

similar.



In any case, this histogram is recorded once per cookie access, which

means it's skewed by clients that make more network requests. More

useful is the API.StorageAccess.RequestStorageAccess2 histogram

(recorded by renderers for each rSA call) and the

API.StorageAccess.RequestOutcome histogram (recorded by the browser

for each storage-access permission request).



An added bonus of this removal is that the SAA lookups can become

lazier; we no longer have to search through content settings unless

the appropriate CookieSettingOverride is present.



OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[API.StorageAccess.InputState]=deleted since it's less useful than other histograms; see the CL description for details.

entry.title: [mullhet] Generate manual fallback password suggestions.
entry.content:
This CL implements a basic password manual fallback suggestion

generation logic. Suggestions are created for every CredentialUIEntry.

If the password is affiliated with multiple domains, only the first

domain is used to create the suggestion. First level list of suggestions

is sorted by the displayed domain name.



Each suggestion has 3 child suggestions to fill username, password

(password is not displayed) and open UI window to view the password

details.



Logic to handle these suggestions will be implemented in the

future CLs. Current suggestions also lack domain web site icons.

entry.title: iwa: Properly support IWAs in `windows.create`
entry.content:
Isolated Web Apps [1] always run in standalone app browser windows and

cannot be opened in normal browser windows. This is enforced by checks

in `BrowserNavigator`, which automatically moves tabs that navigate to

an installed IWA, and that are not yet in a separate window, into a

standalone window.



The `windows.create` extension API, when used with the `url` parameter

set to an `isolated-app:` URL did not play nicely with IWAs:

It created two browser windows when launching an IWA, the first being

a normal tabbed window, and the second being a proper standalone app

window created due to the code in `BrowserNavigator`.



This CL fixes the behavior by doing two things:

1. It relaxes the restrictions in `BrowserNavigator` to allow creation

of a tab in an IWA window with `NEW_*_TAB` dispositions in addition

to the `CURRENT_TAB` disposition, if there is not yet a tab in the

IWA window.

2. It updates the `windows.create` code:

- Creates an app window for isolated-app: URLs.

- Adds an error if it is called with more than one URL and one of the

URLs is an isolated-app: URL.

- Adds an error if the isolated-app: URL is malformatted.

- Adds an error if `url` contains an isolated-app: URL and `tabId` is

set as well.

- Adds an error if `tabId` refers to an `isolated-app:` tab.

- Adds an error when trying to open a window with a `type` other than

`normal`.



[1]: https://github.com/WICG/isolated-web-apps
